ese republicans directly influenced and guided the US-based militant republican organisation, Clan na Gael, transformed the overall dynamics of militant Irish republicanism in America and provided leadership and co-ordination for an IRA bombing campaign. With the inclusion of these veterans’ stories, the book provides a fresh interpretation of the inter-war movement in America that shows it to be far from as stagnant, wayward and detached from Irish affairs as has previously been claimed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIrish question. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Terrorism.2bisacsh  aAnti-Treaty.  aClan na Gael.  aIRA bombing campaign.  aIrish Republican Army.  aIrish-American.  aSecond World War.  aacademic.  ageneral audience.  amilitant Irish republican movement.  atransnational.1 aWilk, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packagez978311128357940uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779951740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847799517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847799517/original  a978-3-11-128357-9  Manchester University Press 2014 eBook-Packageb2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles